            "title": "My Ex-Husband Sexually Abused His Sister. Should I Have Been Warned? - The New York Times",
            "published_date": "2023-01-10T10:00:07.000Z",
            "authors": null,
            "description": "The magazine\u2019s Ethicist columnist on who has the right to know about someone\u2019s dark past.",
            "section": "Magazine",
            "content": "When my ex-husband left me, I received a series of texts from his sister. She and I had a close relationship for the 16-year duration of my marriage, which started when she was a teenager. In the texts, she told me that I should be happy to be rid of him. When I questioned her, she told me that he sexually abused her when she was 5 and he was 12. She had told her parents, who put an end to it, but she and her brother didn\u2019t receive any healing therapy. It was swept under the rug. I sat on this shocking and disturbing information for a few days, had him confirm it and then wrote back to my now-former sister-in-law that I was heartbroken for her and devastated to learn that this was the person I had married. I also told her that I felt hurt that she was telling me only now: Why had his entire family known about this horrible thing and let me marry him and have children with him? She responded by saying that my ex-husband and I deserved each other, and she and I haven\u2019t spoken since. Am I wrong to be angry that the entire family kept me in the dark and that they let me enter into a union with a monster like that and didn\u2019t worry about my children when they came along? Was she wrong to tell me after the fact \u2014 should I have been left in ignorance? If he remarries someone with children, should she be warned? I have not told my children, but if they have babies of their own, should I let them know so he is never alone with our grandchildren? Where does it end? This causes me many sleepless nights, even though we\u2019ve now been split up for nearly a decade. Name Withheld Whether your in-laws should have told you what your fianc\u00e9 did when he was 12 depends, in part, on what they thought it signified about his behavior as an adult. Having, as your sister-in-law says, put an end to it, and having no evidence that he had done anything similar later on, they might well have thought it was behind him and that he posed no danger to children, including any you might have.\n\nCould they have been right about this? You don\u2019t say you have any evidence that he abused children as an adult. Statistically speaking, juveniles who commit sex crimes \u2014 as your in-laws may have known \u2014 do seem to be different from adults who do so; the available research suggests that few such juveniles reoffend when they are grown up. It\u2019s nonetheless unfortunate that no therapy was offered to the siblings. Adolescents who have offended seem to respond better to treatment than adults do, and your sister-in-law is clearly still distressed by what happened and by the way her family handled the matter. Suppose your then-fianc\u00e9, as seems typical of those with a history like his, posed no threat to children. Did you have a right to know that the person you planned to marry had, at a young age, done a terrible thing, even if he wasn\u2019t prone to do anything like it again? We rightly try not to define adults by offenses they committed as children. Still, you could feel that his family should have urged him to tell you about it and allowed him to express whatever remorse and revulsion he might have come to feel about his childhood acts. But that\u2019s all in the past; you\u2019ve been divorced for years. Contemplating the future, you wonder whether you may, one day, have to inform other people in your ex-husband\u2019s life about his juvenile misconduct in order to protect their children. No doubt you\u2019re worried that your motives here are mixed: The resentment you clearly feel toward this man might lead you to pass on the news just to embarrass him. I note that you were able to call him to ask if his sister\u2019s allegations were true. He gave you an honest answer. If circumstances arise in which you wonder whether you should tell someone about his past, you might talk to him first and listen to what he has to say in response. My sister and her husband have a very negative parenting style with their son. They are constantly yelling at him or telling him he\u2019s doing something wrong. The child does act out sometimes. They have sent him to therapy before, but not with much success, and they don\u2019t seem to recognize that their parenting style may be influencing his behavior. It has gotten to the point that several of my family members have commented on their negativity, and it\u2019s difficult to spend time with them. We do get along well with their son, and so do my kids. Once, when I had a young child and they didn\u2019t yet have children, I needed to have a conversation with my sister because she and her husband were not nice to my son. It\u2019s one thing to bring up adults\u2019 bad behavior when it\u2019s directed at your own child; it\u2019s harder when it\u2019s their parenting style toward their own child. What should I do? I feel stuck, because I do not want to ruin my family\u2019s relationship with her family. Name Withheld\n\nYou\u2019re right that it\u2019s much easier to complain when people mistreat your child than when they mistreat their own. But aunts and uncles have a place in shaping a child\u2019s life, especially if that child is going to be around their own children. The trouble is that people are sensitive about criticism of their parenting, including criticism from those they know are motivated by love. The fact that this child has been in therapy suggests his parents are aware that there\u2019s a problem, even if they don\u2019t see that they are part of it. I wonder whether, with your encouragement, they might be willing to consider family therapy. An independent expert might be in a position to recognize their badgering behavior as harmful and suggest strategies for a more positive approach. I live in an apartment in San Francisco, and for the last two years, I have been subjected to uncontrolled dog barking, door slamming and loud talking from an obnoxious neighbor. I have a brain injury that \u2014 as I told the neighbor the first day she moved in \u2014 makes me painfully sensitive to loud, repetitive noise. She has since acquired a second poorly behaved dog (the first is supposedly a support animal) and a loud boyfriend, and now works loudly on speakerphone from home all day, adjacent to my bedroom wall. The landlady told me this is my problem and to work it out. I have done all I can think of to adjust myself, but the noise is audible over earplugs and headphones. We are a family of three who have lived here for decades, in an affordable apartment that we need. I would appreciate your perspective. Name Withheld I assume that you have raised these issues with your neighbor; given that she knows about your disability, her behavior seems especially unkind. At this point, you might explore potential legal remedies. You won\u2019t be losing a friend if you take advantage of them, in light of your neighbor\u2019s apparent indifference toward maintaining civil relations. In San Francisco, you can certainly ask the city to check whether the sounds exceed the legal limit, although responsibility for noise control is distributed among several municipal departments. (Audio recordings might be helpful in this situation.) Going to war against people you live among can have noxious consequences. As for where to direct the request, you could call 311 and ask for guidance or you could confer with the right kind of lawyer \u2014 probably a landlord-tenant lawyer. Your landlord told you that this was your problem to deal with, but according to a summary of the administrative codes published by the San Francisco Police Department, she has a legal duty \u201cto exercise diligence to minimize exposure to noise.\u201d A lawyer\u2019s letter could remind her of these responsibilities. You might have grounds to file a private nuisance suit against your landlord or against your neighbor. Even if the noise level is not illegal, you can go to Community Boards, a local nonprofit conflict-resolution agency, to seek mediation.",
            "link": "https://www.nytimes.com/2023/01/10/magazine/child-sexual-abuse-ethics.html"
