            "content": "As a subscriber, you have 10 gift articles to give each month. Anyone can read what you share.\n\nTUESDAY PUZZLE \u2014 Congratulations to Emily Rourke, who is making her second appearance as a New York Times Crossword constructor. Today\u2019s puzzle is a simple, cheerful example of how a phrase or term can be reinterpreted into a wordplay revealer that an entire puzzle can be built around. One of my favorite things about writing this column is learning about what sparks the initial idea for a constructor\u2019s theme. These kernels of inspiration have included posters at a gym, viral YouTube videos and plenty of other silly jumping-off points. Today\u2019s puzzle was inspired by Ms. Rourke\u2019s cat \u2014 and I\u2019m sure solvers will see why. But before we get to the theme, let\u2019s examine a few of today\u2019s tougher clues. 1A. People who eschew musical theater may not know that the \u201c\u2018Rent\u2019 character who sings \u2018Light my Candle\u2019\u201d is MIMI. Fun fact: \u201cRent\u201d is loosely based on the Giacomo Puccini opera \u201cLa Boh\u00e8me,\u201d in which another character named MIMI requests help lighting a candle.\n\n50A. I don\u2019t know whether I would have chosen to use the clue \u201c___ Gay (W.W. II plane)\u201d for ENOLA, the name of the plane that dropped an atomic bomb on Japan, especially given today\u2019s (Japan-adjacent) theme. ENOLA Holmes is always an alternative clue option for this word. 52A. The clue \u201cSong refrain syllable\u201d is often used for TRA, which is also part of the singsong \u201cTRA la la.\u201d In fact, TRA has appeared with a similar clue more than 500 times in the New York Times Crossword. 34D. I\u2019m most familiar with the word PETARD in the context of the expression \u201choisted on his own PETARD,\u201d which has always led me to believe that a PETARD was something like a flagpole. Instead, a PETARD is an \u201cOld explosive device used to breach castle walls.\u201d I definitely wouldn\u2019t want to be hoisted on one of those \u2014 my own or otherwise! 41D. \u201c\u2018___, sure, you betcha!\u2019 (classic Minnesotan expression)\u201d is a fun fill-in-the-blank clue for YAH, which I can\u2019t even mentally read without pronouncing it in an exaggerated Minnesotan accent.\n\nThis puzzle features four familiar felines and a revealer that instructs you on how you might greet them: HELLO KITTY. The revealer clue at 39A reads, \u201cFictional feline from Japan \u2026 or how one might greet 17-, 24-, 54- or 65-Across.\u201d Each of the theme clues contains the name of another fictional feline:\n\u2022 None 17A. PINK PANTHER (\u201cTitular animated character whose theme music is by Henry Mancini\u201d)\n\u2022 None 24A. TONY THE TIGER (\u201cCereal mascot who says \u2018They\u2019re gr-r-reat!\u2019\u201d) Now, I\u2019m not generally a stickler for the lore surrounding fictional felines, but I did recently learn (from a \u201cSaturday Night Live\u201d sketch, below, and from a Los Angeles Times article I read after seeing it) that HELLO KITTY is not, in fact, a feline. According to Sanrio, the company that owns the rights to HELLO KITTY, she is a little British girl who lives with her parents, her twin sister and pet cat (!!!) named Charmmy Kitty.\n\nIn my view, that \u201cfact,\u201d insofar as there can be \u201cfacts\u201d about fictional characters, doesn\u2019t make this theme any less charming (charmmy?). This is a tidy set of fictional felines tied together by a fun revealer that may or may not also be about a fictional feline. What\u2019s not to love? And there you have it! Kudos to Ms. Rourke on this puzzle. Let\u2019s hear from her about the origins of this puzzle and her own nonfictional feline. I was inspired to construct a feline-themed crossword after we adopted our cat, Sperry, in 2021. Every day she sits in my lap as I complete the New York Times Crossword, so it seems fitting that her feline family members feature in a puzzle of their own. Cereal is also an important component of my morning crossword routine, so I\u2019m pleased that 24-Across made it into the final version. I had a lot of fun diving into the universe of fictional cats, and my only regret was having to cut Puss in Boots. Happy New Year and happy solving! Want to Submit Crosswords to The New York Times? The New York Times Crossword has an open submission system, and you can submit your puzzles online.\n\n\n\nFor tips on how to get started, read our series, \u201cHow to Make a Crossword Puzzle.\u201d Almost finished solving but need a bit more help? We\u2019ve got you covered. Spoiler alert: Subscribers can take a peek at the answer key. Trying to get back to the main Gameplay page? You can find it here.",
