            "title": "Hochul\u2019s Vision for New York: Fighting Crime and Building Housing - The New York Times",
            "published_date": "2023-01-10T16:18:59.000Z",
            "authors": null,
            "description": "Gov. Kathy Hochul delivered a State of the State speech on Tuesday that addressed what she said were the most pressing issues for New Yorkers.",
            "section": "New York",
            "content": "As a subscriber, you have 10 gift articles to give each month. Anyone can read what you share.\n\nGov. Kathy Hochul delivered a State of the State speech on Tuesday that addressed what she said were the most pressing issues for New Yorkers.\n\nALBANY, N.Y. \u2014 Making crime and affordability the cornerstones of her State of the State address, Gov. Kathy Hochul of New York on Tuesday sought to offer a road map to address the vexing and deep-rooted problems that are facing most metropolitan areas across the country, and are acutely felt in New York City. Many of her plans seemed squarely aimed at helping New York City navigate its pandemic-era recovery, as Mayor Eric Adams wrestles with residents\u2019 fears over street and subway crime, as well as a visible increase in New Yorkers who are homeless and mentally ill. Indeed, Ms. Hochul saved some of her loftiest rhetoric to describe her proposals to overhaul the state\u2019s approach to mental health, an issue championed by Mr. Adams, promising \u201ca monumental shift to make sure no one falls through the cracks.\u201d She said she would order hospitals to free up 850 inpatient psychiatric beds and enact changes to provide more care to people after they are discharged. Ms. Hochul, a Democrat who was elected to a full term in November, committed to hiring more prosecutors and proposed to give judges more latitude when setting bail, a move that seems likely to revive a bitter yearslong debate in Albany about criminal justice reforms.\n\nThe governor also promised to shore up the finances of New York City\u2019s subway system to avoid fare hikes and service reductions, and reiterated her support for converting office buildings in Manhattan, as well as currently illegal basements, into housing to address a dire shortage. She also tackled two other crises affecting the city, high rents and homelessness, unveiling an ambitious plan to build more than 800,000 new units of housing statewide over the next 10 years \u2014 twice what New York has built in the last decade. Even the front cover of the 277-page book outlining her policies was telling: It featured an outline of the city\u2019s skyline and major landmarks, but paid no similar homage to other regions of the state. The State of the State address was Ms. Hochul\u2019s first since winning a full term and becoming the first woman elected governor of New York. Indeed, the election, one of the closest New York governor\u2019s race in decades, cast a shadow over her agenda after Republicans made inroads last year by focusing on public safety and the state\u2019s high costs of living. \u201cIf New Yorkers don\u2019t feel safe in our communities, if they can\u2019t afford to buy a home or pay the rent, then the dream stays out of reach for them,\u201d Ms. Hochul told lawmakers gathered in the State Capitol\u2019s cavernous Assembly chamber during a 45-minute speech.\n\nTo help New Yorkers most affected by soaring prices, Ms. Hochul announced a plan to ensure the state\u2019s minimum wage kept pace with inflation, so that the lowest-paid workers would not continue to see their buying power diminish. Ms. Hochul offered other far-ranging commitments that could reverberate statewide. She vowed to expand access to child care. She doubled down on efforts to reduce greenhouse gas emissions. And she sought to boost the agriculture industry by seeking to increase the percentage of local food products that state agencies must purchase. But the thrust of her address was undeniably crime and affordability, pressing themes that both Democrats and Republicans in Albany have already said will dominate this year\u2019s legislative session, and are likely to expose major rifts. On crime, Republicans, who are mostly powerless in the minority, are continuing to clamor for the repeal of the divisive changes Democrats made to the state\u2019s bail laws in 2019, an issue they amplified during last year\u2019s election as they sought to blame Democrats for a spike in crime. Ms. Hochul\u2019s decision to pursue further revisions to the laws seems likely to put her, as well as Mayor Adams, who has vocally pushed for changes, on a collision course with the more left-leaning factions of the State Legislature once again. (There was notably no applause from Democrats in the chamber when she said the bail laws had \u201croom for improvement.\u201d) Months before the pandemic disrupted life across the country, New York made all but the most serious crimes ineligible for bail. In those instances where bail was set, judges were instructed to use the \u201cleast restrictive\u201d means necessary to ensure defendants returned to court, and to avoid setting bail that a defendant would be unable to pay. Last session, Ms. Hochul secured a bevy of changes designed to tighten the bail laws, adding to the list of crimes eligible for bail as well as to the criteria judges were able to consider, while preserving the \u201cleast restrictive\u201d standard.\n\nOn Tuesday, Ms. Hochul proposed lifting that standard in some cases, freeing judges to make their decisions based on factors like the seriousness of the charges and an individual\u2019s history of using a gun. The change would seem to implement a de facto \u201cdangerousness\u201d standard for bail-eligible crimes, while leaving in place a more lenient standard for less serious offenses. Ms. Hochul also said she would commit more than $36 million to hire hundreds of prosecutors to help process case backlogs around the state, and to address rises in violent crime as well as gun and property crime. The governor simultaneously put forth a far-reaching plan to tackle the dire shortage of housing statewide, but especially in New York City and its suburbs, where housing costs that are among the highest in the nation have contributed to a severe homelessness crisis. Ms. Hochul framed her housing plan as an imperative to lower costs, along with the number of people flocking to other states, blaming New York localities for imposing land-use regulations and construction bans she said were the \u201cmost restrictive in the nation.\u201d \u201cPeople want to live here, they have jobs here, but because of local decisions that limit growth, they cannot,\u201d Ms. Hochul said, name-checking other large cities building housing at a faster rate than New York City. \u201cLocal governments can and should make a difference.\u201d Taking cues from other states such as California, Ms. Hochul proposed that New York State play a more active role in shaping housing policy by coercing cities, towns and villages to ease restrictions that have stunted housing production. To meet the goal of 800,000 new units, Ms. Hochul is pushing for the construction of more housing around commuter rail and subway stations. She is also asking municipalities downstate to increase the number of homes by 3 percent over three years, a change that could make a big difference on Long Island, for example, which saw its number of new homes increase by just over half a percent between 2018 and 2020.\n\nHer proposal could spark tension. If a locality does not meet its state-imposed housing target, it may trigger a special process allowing developers to propose and build bigger buildings, even without the local government\u2019s approval. The state estimates these targets will allow for almost 150,000 new homes over the next decade. Ms. Hochul forecast that another 400,000 units could be constructed, in part, by passing a modified version of a contentious tax break for real estate developers that had helped spur the construction of rental housing in New York City but expired last year amid disagreements with Democrats who control the State Legislature. Ms. Hochul\u2019s proposals incorporate many of the goals of an ascendant pro-housing movement in New York, but could prove difficult to muscle through the Legislature, where some are likely to draw fierce resistance from local officials and the party\u2019s left wing. In the coming weeks, Ms. Hochul will release her state budget proposal, which will outline how much the governor\u2019s plans will cost. She will then have until April 1 to negotiate the state budget with lawmakers, a typically tense, back-room process of deal making during which most of Albany\u2019s policy battles are waged. This year, the governor will head into the negotiations already at odds with Democrats in the State Senate who have mounted a surprisingly forceful opposition to Ms. Hochul\u2019s nominee for chief judge of the state\u2019s highest court, raising the specter of a chaotic confirmation clash later this month. Citing dire forecasts about a potential recession, Ms. Hochul said on Tuesday that she would not look to increase income taxes, a move favored by a coalition of left-wing activists. But she vowed to help the city\u2019s public transit system tackle a budget crisis that had been triggered, in part, by a steep pandemic-era drop in ridership. To that end, Ms. Hochul said the state was about to move a major step closer to adopting a congestion-pricing program that would charge a toll as high as $23 to motorists who enter Manhattan below 60th Street. The fee, which would finance improvements to the transit network, will require final approval from the board of the Metropolitan Transportation Authority.",
            "link": "https://www.nytimes.com/2023/01/10/nyregion/hochul-ny-state-of-state.html"
