n troops, who have shown themselves to be quick studies on military systems, might be able to get up to speed more quickly. For the Biden administration, the unusual step of U.S.-based training does not risk escalation with Russia, as Patriot is a defensive system that is meant to protect Ukrainians from Russian missiles, not an offensive one.\n\n4. Protests over the ouster of Peru\u2019s former president have led to at least 46 deaths. At least 17 people were killed yesterday in southern Peru in an extraordinary spasm of violence that led to criticism of excessive force by the military and the police. The country has been the scene of violent demonstrations since mid-December, when its leftist president, Pedro Castillo, who had promised to address longstanding issues of poverty and inequality, attempted to dissolve Congress and rule by decree. The move was widely condemned as unconstitutional, and he was arrested and replaced by his vice president. Since then, his supporters, many of them living in impoverished rural regions, have taken to the streets to demand new general elections. The recent clashes heightened concerns that the protests would continue to spread and lead to more bloodshed. In other international news, our reporter explored the fragile power alliance in the Philippines between President Ferdinand Marcos Jr. and Sara Duterte, the scions of two notorious family dynasties.\n\n5. Trillions of dollars in government spending is beginning to alter the labor market. The primary purpose of recent federal legislation \u2014 $1.2 trillion from the 2021 infrastructure bill, $370 billion in the climate bill and $53 billion for semiconductor manufacturing \u2014 was not to stimulate the economy. But as the broader economy cools, the continuing infusion of cash may help avert a sharp dip in employment brought on by the Federal Reserve\u2019s attempts to contain inflation by raising interest rates. The investments are also likely to spur the reallocation of workers across sectors.\n\n6. The last eight years were the hottest on record. The world remained a hotter planet last year, with extreme summer temperatures in Europe, China and elsewhere contributing to 2022 being the fifth-hottest year on record, European climate researchers said. Even more concerning: The eight warmest years on record have now occurred since 2014, and 2016 remains the hottest year ever. Overall, the world is now 2.1 degrees Fahrenheit (1.2 degrees Celsius) hotter than it was in the second half of the 19th century, when emissions of planet-warming carbon dioxide from the burning of fossil fuels became widespread. In the U.S., greenhouse gas emissions rose by 1.3 percent last year, moving the nation in the opposite direction from its climate goals.\n\nAs a traveling wrestler, Donovan Danhausen mainly survived off his paycheck from his day job at Starbucks. Then he found a new gimmick: He created a new character, an evil demon, who evolved into an eccentric and bumbling version of one after audiences were drawn to his humor. Soon, the ghoulish Danhausen became a kind of commentary on wrestling itself. With a physical presence somewhere between frail and confused, Danhausen became the kind of wrestler that resonates deeply with the class of obsessive fans who attend indie shows. \u201cWrestling is a parody of sports,\u201d a fellow wrestler said. \u201cBut this is now a parody of that parody.\u201d",
